This is a great race - I ran in memory of my uncle Jim who did this every year (always ran in a straw hat). Jim passed away this summer in a bicycle crash - the course goes by his house so it was a great way to see family and tribute him. The straw hat had a bit of drag - but his friends from his running club appreciated it. As far as the running - I felt good energy and fitness wise. First 7 I had to focus on slowing down. From 9 on my hamstring locked up - don't know why. Even though I felt good, I could only do 6:50 ish. Hamstring just wouldn't let me go faster. Got to figure out what's up. 2 days ago

Got third, but it was a comedy of errors.  Way to hot to be a time day, so was thinking of place over that.  Settled into 2/3 at the mile mark, and stayed there until the turn around, which is where the errors began.  First, going around the cone - my feet flew out from under me thanks to some loose gravel.  The guy with me was a good sport and waited/helped me up.  However, I couldn't really get it back.  My quad/hip seized up a bit when I fell.  Also, I spilled my water before I got any... which is the start of another string of errors.  The next water stop had some many people going the other way that I missed it.  The following was set up on the wrong side of the road, but went across to get some.  The following wasn't ready so I didn't get any....  basically I got a sip of water from 4-11 and was hurting by the end.  Anyway, not happy with the time, but glad to to hang on to third.
I think it would have been better to take today off.  Quad still catching and knee a little swollen from yesterday's tumble.  Took it easy, but still bothered me.

Goal was to run MP - which was tougher than anticipated due to a challenging course, lots of wind, running mostly alone, sore back ... oh and my fitness is behind where I would like to be (the biggest reason).

Pretty happy to happy to get 13 MP miles in, faded a little but at the end which is a reminder that I have a lot of work to do.  Also struggled with a sore low back and left hip/glute which Ill need to work on.

Got to the track alone on a rainy night - so spur of the moment decided to do one set of the Quenton Cassidy 400s workout:  5x(4x400 w/ 100 jog rest between) and 400 jog between sets.  I made a few MINOR modifications:  I took 500m rest between sets so I could start each in the same place and not loose track, I ran 81-84 instead of 61-64 with most at 82, I did one instead of 3 sets of 20, I did not pee blood.

I would like to do this again when training for the mile and be more in mile pace + 3-4s range.

Interesting race, only noticed that there wasnt clock when I was on the line. As normal, wasnt wearing a watch, so turned to Joe and just told him I was going to trust his pacing.  Since our heat was mostly high-schoolers, we planned on getting to the back assuming they were going to start fast.

At the start the runner in lane 1 fell, so it was stopped and we lined up again.

On the second attempt, we got to the back as planned, but it seemed to go out slow.  So joe started moving up, and I just tried to follow.  The first 800 has lots of contact, I got clipped  almost fell, a few times we had to abruptly slow to avoid getting caught up. Joe later told me we went through 800
In 2:32. 

At 800 joe noticeably increased the pace and I followed with a couple nifty moves to pass on his part.  We took the lead at 1200 and pushed over the last 400 to go 1/2 in the heat.  Joe did all the work/thinking.  I was appreciative to just follow.   Never felt that I was in trouble, but definitely had marathon legs and didnt have much for a top end gear.
